# stdlib/effects.kai — proposed atomic effect catalog (forward-compat).
#
# **Status (m12.8.x phase 4 — 2026-04-26): documentation only.** This
# file is intentionally inert — no `effect` or `type` declarations are
# emitted. The compiler does not need to parse it today, and loading
# it via `--prelude stdlib/effects.kai` is a no-op.
#
# The proposed catalog below documents the target shape of the
# follow-up lane (call it Phase 4b / m12.8.z) that completes the
# effects-prelude row enforcement and splits `Console` into its
# component streams. Until then:
#
#   - `print(s)`    is a flat prelude builtin (typer does not require
#                   the caller to declare `/ Stdout` or `/ Console`).
#   - `eprint(s)`   ditto.
#   - `read_line()` ditto for `/ Stdin`.
#   - `read_file`/`write_file` ditto for `/ File`.
#   - `Console`     is a single combined effect with `print` + `eprint`
#                   in the runtime ABI.
#
# CLAUDE.md Tier 1 #1 ("every effect a function uses appears in its
# row") is therefore violated by user code that calls `print`
# directly without declaring a row. The follow-up lane closes that
# gap. The blocker for landing it inside m12.8.x phase 4 was the
# selfhost path: stage 1 (kaikai-minimal) cannot parse row syntax on
# fn signatures, so adding rows to `stage2/compiler.kai`'s
# print/eprint helpers breaks the bootstrap. See
# `docs/m12.8-followup.md` Bug 6 for the full scoping note and the
# two paths forward (extend stage 1's parser to accept-and-ignore row
# annotations, or gate the row enforcement on an opt-in marker).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Proposed (Phase 4b) shape
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# effect Stdin {
#   read_line() : Result[String, String]
# }
#
# effect Stdout {
#   print(s: String) : Unit
# }
#
# effect Stderr {
#   eprint(s: String) : Unit
# }
#
# effect File {
#   read_file(path: String)                   : Result[String, String]
#   write_file(path: String, content: String) : Result[Unit, String]
# }
#
# effect Env {
#   env_get(key: String) : Option[String]
# }
#
# type Console = Stdout + Stderr + Stdin
# type Io      = Console + Env + File
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# NetTcp (net-tcp-v1 lane, 2026-05-02)
#
# The byte-level TCP networking effect. Six ops, declared in the
# compiler's `builtin_nettcp_decl` (stage2/compiler.kai) so the typer
# always sees them; the matching default handler is installed around
# `main` when its row mentions `/ NetTcp`. Spec: docs/effects-stdlib.md
# §`NetTcp`. Catalog row ships in this file as documentation only,
# matching the rest of the v1 effects-prelude.
#
# effect NetTcp {
#   connect(host: String, port: Int)              : Result[String, Conn]
#   listen(host: String, port: Int)               : Result[String, Listener]
#   accept(l: Listener)                           : Result[String, Conn]
#   send(c: Conn, data: [Int])                    : Result[String, Int]
#   recv(c: Conn, max: Int)                       : Result[String, [Int]]
#   close(c: Conn)                                : Unit
# }
#
# Two divergences from the spec in docs/effects-stdlib.md:
#
#   1. `[Byte]` -> `[Int]`. Kaikai has no first-class Byte type yet.
#      `type Byte = Int` was attempted but the stage 2 typer's
#      `resolve_ty` does not substitute non-effect type aliases — a
#      Byte alias would leave Byte a distinct nominal that does not
#      unify with Int. Switching to `[Int]` keeps the surface honest
#      until a real Byte lands. Each element is expected to be in
#      [0, 255]; the runtime truncates higher bits.
#
#   2. Result type-arg order. The spec writes `Result[Conn, String]`
#      Rust-style (Ok first), but kaikai's `Result[e, a]` is
#      Err-first / Ok-second (see add_builtin_variant_sigs in
#      stage2/compiler.kai — the `Ok` constructor takes the second
#      type parameter). The catalog above flips the order so user
#      code can write `match NetTcp.connect(...) { Ok(c) -> ...
#      Err(msg) -> ... }` with `c: Conn` and `msg: String`.
#
# # Opaque handles. v1 keeps them as records with implementation-
# # defined fields. The `port` slot on Listener exists so a server
# # bound to port 0 can read back the kernel-assigned port via
# # `net.tcp.local_port` without needing a separate effect op.
# type Conn      = { fd: Int }
# type Listener  = { fd: Int, port: Int }
#
# v1 limitations vs the pinned spec:
#   - IPv4 only (AF_INET). The handler does not try AF_INET6.
#   - All ops are blocking on the OS thread: the m8.x cooperative
#     scheduler (landed v0.4.0) suspends fibers on mailbox / await /
#     yield, but socket calls have no readiness reactor wired in
#     yet. kqueue / epoll integration is a Tier 2 follow-up tracked
#     in docs/fibers-honesty-targets.md §Reactor.
#   - `Listener` has no close op. The kernel reclaims the listening
#     socket at process exit; long-running servers are out of scope
#     for this lane.
#   - The full `Net` alias (`type Net = NetTcp + NetUdp + NetDns`)
#     waits on the NetUdp / NetDns lanes; declaring it before the
#     atomics land would dangle.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Signal (issue #107, 2026-05-02)
#
# POSIX signal trap for graceful shutdown — the upstream gap that
# blocked lnds/ahu's `run_app` Tongariki lane and lnds/manutara's
# Ctrl-C drain story. Three ops in v1, modelled on/off/await
# rather than the BEAM-faithful on_cancel(sig) shape sketched in
# the issue: v1 cannot honour user-installed Cancel handlers on
# runtime-triggered cancellation (see `kai_default_cancel_raise`
# in stage0/runtime.h), so on_cancel would degrade to exit(0) for
# main without ever running the user's cleanup. on/off/await
# implements the trap synchronously via sigwait — the BEAM-style
# variant is queued for the m8.x scheduler lane, alongside Cancel
# delivery from runtime origin.
#
# Catalog row ships in the compiler's `builtin_signal_decl`
# (stage2/compiler.kai); the matching default handler is installed
# around `main` when its row mentions `/ Signal`. Spec:
# docs/effects-stdlib.md §`Signal`. Sig variant names are the
# runtime contract — adding a new variant requires a paired entry
# in stage0/runtime.h's `kai_signal_entries[]`.
#
# type Sig = SigInt | SigTerm | SigHup | SigUsr1 | SigUsr2
#
# effect Signal {
#   on(sig: Sig)  : Unit
#   off(sig: Sig) : Unit
#   await()       : Sig
# }
#
# v1 limitations:
#   - Posix only. Windows / WASM mapping deferred to the same lane
#     as non-Posix I/O backends.
#   - `await()` blocks the OS thread; reactor-driven non-blocking
#     integration with Spawn is m8.x scope.
#   - SIGCHLD intentionally absent (Process.wait reaps).
#   - Real-time signals (SIGRTMIN+n) and siginfo_t out of scope.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
